What we will do here is : 

1.Launch an Ec2 Instance 
2.Intall Node.js 
3.Create backend application 
4.Create a systemd service
5.Configure Nginx reverse proxy 
5.Test the app in browser 

Step 1: Launch Ec2 Instance 
---------------------------
1.Go to the AWS console  -> Ec2 
2.Click on launch instance -> and name it as backend-server
3.Select the machine image or use the existing image
4.Instance type: t2.micro
5.Key pair : Create /choose already existing one 
6.Security Group : Allow SSH (22) and http (80)
8.Launch the Instance

Step 2: Connect to the Ec2
---------------------------
SSH into the instance
>> ssh -i keypairfilepath.pem username@public_IP_address

Step 3: Here we are using the Node.js for the backend purpose 
-------------------------------------------------------------

 Intall the Node.js and Nginx

 >> sudo apt update -y
 >> curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | sudo -E bash -    # this command prepares  your ubuntu  systems so that you can install Node.js 18 using apt
 >> sudo apt install -y  nodejs nginx

Check the node version : 
>> node -v

Step 4: Crate a Node.js app
------------------------------------------------------------
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/app
sudo tee /var/www/app/server.js > /dev/null <<EOF
const express = requires("express");
const app = express();
app.get("/",(req,res)=> {
  res.send("hello from node.js server!");
});
app.listen(3000,() => console.log("App running on port 3000"));
EOF

Install dependencies:
>> sudo npm install expresss --prefix /var/www/app

Step 5: Create systemmd Service
-----------------------------------------------------------
sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/nodeapp.service > /dev/null <<EOF
[Unit]                              # Service Metadata
Description=Node.js APP
After=network.target                # this tells "Start the service after the network is up"

[Service]                                            # This tells how the app run 
ExecStart=/usr/bin/node /var/www/app/server.js       # The exact command that systemcd runs when starting your app it runs the Node.js and loads the server file
Restart= always                                      # Other options available are on-failure,no,on-abort
User=root                                            # Runs the app as root user which is not recommended ,use other user 
WorkingDirectory=/var/www/app                        # Systemd will cd into this directory before running your app

[Install]                                            # When to start the service
WantedBy=multi-user.target                           # start the servive automatically at boot normal multi-user mdoe 
EOF


Enable the service: 
>> sudo systemctl daemon-reload             #  tells the systemcd to reload all the services  files because something changed     
>> sudo systemctl enable nodeapp            
>> sudo systemctl start nodeapp
>> sudo systemctl status nodeapp

If something goes wrong from the "systemd[1]"  then use this code to check what happened
>> sudo journalctl -u nodeapp --no-pager -n 30       # this command is used to view the log from systemd journal 

This command says : 
show the last 30days lines of the nodeapp service ,without paging [no scrolling ] using the root privileges



The file /etc/systemd/system/nodeapp.service ensures:
*App start automatically at boot
*App never stops
*If app crashes -> systemd restart it 
This is like having a worker whose job is : 
>> Keep the backend app running always
without systemd:
>> App stops as soon as you close the terminal 


| Term                      | Meaning                        |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| **Daemon**                | A background process (service) |
| **systemd**               | The system daemon manager      |
| **daemon-reload**         | Reload service definitions     |
| **sshd / nginx / mysqld** | Examples of daemons            |


Step 6: Configure NGINX Reverse  Proxy 
-------------------------------------------------------------
Open Nginx config:
----------------------
sudo vim /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default

Replace everything with:

server {
      listen 80;

      location / {
          proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000;
          proxy_set_header Host $host;
          proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
      }
}

Then restart the nginx: 
>> sudo systemctl restart nginx

if the nginx doesn't work check the nginx file  "/etc/nginx/site-enabled/default"

Now test in the browser 
>> http://<Ec2_public_IP>




